  <!-- ANSWER CAPSULE: What is bail like in Logan County? -->
  <section style="padding: 48px 1.5rem; background: var(--slate-50);">
    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px;">How Does Bail Work in Logan County, Oklahoma?</h2>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-700); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Angel Bail Bonds provides 24/7 bail bond services for anyone arrested in Logan County, Oklahoma. The Logan County Jail at 216 South Broad Street in Guthrie books inmates around the clock. After bail is set, Angel Bail Bonds can post the bond and most defendants are released within 1 to 4 hours. We are located just 33 miles from Guthrie and handle Logan County bonds daily.</strong></p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">When someone is arrested in Logan County, they are transported to the Logan County Jail in Guthrie for booking. The booking process includes identification verification, fingerprinting, a health screening, and entry of charges into the system. Once booking is complete and bail has been set — either through the preset bond schedule or by a judge — a bail bond can be posted to secure release.</p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">Logan County uses a preset bond schedule for many routine charges, which means defendants can post bail without waiting for a court appearance. For more serious offenses or felony charges, a judge must set bail at an arraignment hearing. Logan County arraignments are held on Tuesdays and Thursdays at 1:30 PM at the Logan County Courthouse, 301 E. Harrison Street, Guthrie, OK 73044.</p>

      <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 28px; margin-bottom: 12px;">What Is the Logan County Courthouse Arraignment Schedule?</h3>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-700); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Logan County arraignments are held every Tuesday and Thursday at 1:30 PM at the Logan County Courthouse, 301 E. Harrison Street, Guthrie, OK 73044. To appear on the docket, contact the Court Clerk at (405) 282-0123 between 8:00 AM and 10:30 AM on the day of the requested appearance.</strong></p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">The historic Logan County Courthouse — built in 1907 and originally serving as Oklahoma's first State Capitol from 1907 to 1910 — handles all criminal, civil, and family domestic cases for Logan County. If your loved one's bail requires a judge's approval, Angel Bail Bonds can coordinate with the court schedule to post the bond as quickly as possible after arraignment.</p>

      <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 28px; margin-bottom: 12px;">How Do I Visit Someone in Logan County Jail?</h3>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-700); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Logan County Jail visitation is by appointment only. Hours are Monday through Friday 7:30 AM to 9:00 PM and Saturday through Sunday 7:30 AM to 2:30 PM. Call the jail at (405) 282-4100 to schedule a visit. An online inmate search is available through the Logan County Sheriff's Office website.</strong></p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">Visitors must call ahead to schedule an appointment — walk-in visits are not permitted. If you need to check on an inmate's status or find out their bail amount, the Logan County Sheriff's Office also offers an online inmate search tool. You can also reach the Records Division at 209 W. Oklahoma Ave., Guthrie, OK 73044 for in-person inquiries.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ABOUT LOGAN COUNTY -->
  <section style="padding: 48px 1.5rem; background: white;">
    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px;">About Logan County, Oklahoma</h2>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">Logan County is located in central Oklahoma with a population of approximately 49,555 residents as of the 2020 Census. The county seat is Guthrie, a historic city of roughly 11,000 people that served as Oklahoma's first state capital from 1907 to 1910. The county covers 749 square miles and is named after U.S. Senator John A. Logan of Illinois.</p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">In addition to Guthrie, Logan County includes the communities of Crescent, Coyle, Mulhall, Orlando, Marshall, Cedar Valley, Cimarron City, and Meridian. Whether the arrest occurs during a traffic stop on I-35, at a Guthrie city event, or anywhere within the Logan County Sheriff's 749-square-mile patrol area, Angel Bail Bonds can help secure a fast release.</p>

      <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 28px; margin-bottom: 12px;">How Far Is Logan County from Stillwater?</h3>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-700); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>The Logan County Jail in Guthrie is approximately 33 miles from Stillwater, a drive of about 33 to 40 minutes via US-177 South and SH-33 West. Angel Bail Bonds handles Logan County bonds regularly and can often coordinate posting remotely by phone, so you may not need to drive to Guthrie at all.</strong></p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">Logan County is one of our closest service areas. Our proximity means we can respond quickly to Logan County arrests at any hour. In many cases, we can complete the entire bail bond process over the phone — you provide the inmate's information and payment, and we handle the rest directly with the Logan County Jail.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
